  "en_notes_asad": [
    {
      "note_no": "29",
      "note": "The operative phrase of this passage is contained in the words, \"anyone who contends against (man hadda) God and His Apostle\": i.e., anyone who is engaged in active hostility against God's message and the person or the teachings of His Apostle. As regards relations with non-behevers who are not actively hostile to Islam, the Qur'an explicitly permits and implicitly ordains in many places (e.g., in 60:89) kindness and friendliness towards them."
    },
    {
      "note_no": "30",
      "note": "For my rendering of iuh as \"inspiration\" or, occasionally, as \"divine inspiration\", see note 2 on 16:2. As pointed out by Zamakhshari, the pronominal suffix in minhu may relate either to God - as in my rendering - or to the believers' faith, in which latter case the phrase could be rendered as \"strengthened with inspiration [flowing] therefrom\"."
    }
